    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-15T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-15T13:00:00-05:00" n="1129"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1129">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/8–1554: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dillon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-08-15T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 15, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>646. Repeated information Saigon 68, Hanoi 7. Limit distribution. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJ1">Sainteny</persName> today told <persName corresp="#p_BPW1"
                        >Bonsal</persName> he is leaving for Hanoi August 18 accompanied by Roland
                    Sadoun. <persName corresp="#p_SJ1">Sainteny</persName> states decision his
                    mission result Viet Minh request at Geneva. He does not anticipate Viet Minh
                    request for reciprocal mission Paris. His functions will, following October 11,
                    be that of French Government representative to a government not recognized by
                    France. He does not as yet have clear idea of just what he can achieve. He
                    believes in trade between North and South Vietnam, notably in rice and coal. He
                    hopes to find helpful elements among non-Communist Viet Minh although recognize
                    they will be fewer and less influential than at time his earlier stay in Hanoi
                    (1945–47). He anticipates French cultural establishments in Hanoi will remain
                    open with present teaching staff.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SJ1">Sainteny</persName> welcomes report he has received
                    of US decision to leave consulate open if possible. “This will be great help to
                    me”.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SJ1">Sainteny</persName> has no views on conditions in
                    South Vietnam. He thinks well of <persName corresp="#p_NDD1"
                    >Diem</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BPW1">Bonsal</persName> also saw <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> this afternoon. Latter had just seen
                        <persName corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendes-France</persName> and had told latter
                    that he, <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>, not disposed to continue in
                    present job if French policy, as reflecting <persName corresp="#p_SJ1"
                        >Sainteny</persName> appointment, was to play double game in <gloss
                        target="#t_IC1">IC</gloss>, i.e., to be prepared through <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJ1">Sainteny</persName> establish full relations Viet Minh if
                    that appears winning card. <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> states
                        <persName corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendes</persName> gave him most categoric
                    assurances that policy of French Government is to give maximum possible support
                    to anti-Communist elements in retained Vietnam and to do everything possible
                    contribute success these elements in pre-electoral period. <persName
                        corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> stated he delighted to hear this, and
                    particularly at fact <persName corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendes</persName> has
                    authorized him to make known policy of French Government at appropriate moment
                    following <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName>’s return to Vietnam (in
                    about a week). <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> continues worried and
                    perplexed at developing political situation in Vietnam including incapacity of
                        <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> government and threat of <hi
                        rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> by religious sects and <persName
                        corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_EGP1"
                        >Ely</persName> states he and <persName corresp="#p_DJ1">Daridan</persName>
                    are in agreement that return of <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> at
                    this time highly undesirable.</p>
                <pb facs="0567" n="1949" xml:id="pg_1949"/>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_EGP1">Ely</persName> expressed in warmest terms
                    appreciation Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName>’s constant
                    cooperation and understanding.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
